value.value: The area around the esophagogastric mucosal junction where the esophageal mucosa transitions into the gastric mucosa.
This gene plays a role in the regulation of protein folding.

Human DNAJB1 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 19p13.2 and is approximately 15 kb in length. This allele, which encodes DnaJ homolog subfamily B member 1 protein, is involved in the modulation of heat shock protein 70 activity. A chromosomal deletion that fuses this gene and the PRKACA gene is associated with fibrolamellar carcinoma.
DnaJ homolog subfamily B member 1 (340 aa, ~38 kDa) is encoded by the human DNAJB1 gene. This protein plays a role in the regulation of both heat shock protein 70 activity and protein folding.

label.value: Coal Gas, Coal Tar, Coal Tar Pitch, and Derivatives

value.value: A complex chemical mixture of condensed-ring aromatic hydrocarbons produced by the destructive distillation (pyrolysis) of coal. The lower viscosity byproducts are generally regarded as tar, whereas the viscous, semisolid, or solid byproducts are designated as pitch. Coal tar and coal tar pitch are known to be human carcinogens.

Any of the monomers, resins, solvents, emulsifiers, intermediates, additives, and others used in the manufacture of rubber and rubber products. Excess deaths from bladder, stomach, lung, hematopoietic, and other cancers have occurred among workers involved in the manufacture of rubber products.
A subscale complement to the FACT-G developed specifically for evaluating the quality of life of cancer patients with neutropenia.
A subscale complement to the FACT-G developed specifically for evaluating the quality of life of patients with multiple myeloma.
A question about whether an individual worries or worried about getting infections.
A question about whether an individual feels or felt discouraged about their illness.
A question about whether an individual worries or worried that they might get new symptoms of their illness.
The portion of the stomach that lies above the cardiac notch. It allows for the accumulation of gases produced by chemical digestion.
A question about whether an individual has or had emotional ups and downs.

label.value: Have Trouble Walking Because of Pain

value.value: A question about whether an individual has or had trouble walking because of pain.
An infectious process caused by rhinovirus. The virus usually causes upper respiratory infections, but can infect the lower tract as well.
A loud, vociferous cry or yell; it can be the result of many emotions, including pain, excitement, or fear.
An exacerbation of the chronic disease lupus.
Laboratory test results demonstrating the presence of the Herpes Simplex virus in a specimen.
An infectious process in which the bacteria Staphylococcus aureus is present.
An acute exacerbation of asthma, characterized by inadequate response to initial bronchodilators.
The sensation of constriction or contraction in the throat area.
A fear of sounds, which can include fear of voices, including one's own voice, in addition to other sounds.
The main section of the digestive tube that connects the esophagus to the small intestine. The body proper excludes the upper and lower sections of the fundus and pyloric portion respectively.
The presence of gas within the wall of the large or small intestine.
Any infection documented following a surgical procedure that was not evident or suspected prior to the procedure.
A laboratory test result demonstrating the presence of bacteria from the genus Pseudomonas in a sample after culture.
Weakness or incomplete paralysis of either the left or right side of the body.

label.value: Borderline Ovarian Serous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Serous Tumor

value.value: A non-invasive serous neoplasm that arises from the ovary and shows greater cellular proliferation and cytologic atypia as compared to benign ovarian serous tumors, but less as compared to low-grade ovarian serous carcinoma.

label.value: Borderline Ovarian Serous Tumor-Micropapillary Variant/Non-Invasive Low Grade Ovarian Serous Carcinoma

value.value: A non-invasive serous neoplasm that arises from the ovary and shows micropapillary and/or cribriform architectural patterns.  It is composed of round epithelial cells with scant cytoplasm and moderate nuclear atypia.

label.value: Borderline Ovarian Mucinous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Mucinous Tumor

value.value: A non-invasive neoplasm that arises from the ovary and is composed of gastrointestinal-type, mucin-containing epithelial cells.  It shows greater cellular proliferation and cytologic atypia as compared to benign ovarian mucinous tumors.
A hollow tube that is inserted and left in the bladder to promote the drainage of urine.
A hollow tube that is inserted in the abdomen to carry fluid into and out of the abdominal cavity.
A hollow tube that is inserted into a large vein to carry blood to and from a dialysis machine.
The initial part of the pyloric canal of the stomach. This site contains endocrine cells that produce gastrin and somatostatin.
A hollow tube that is inserted into a vein.
A central venous catheter inserted through a peripheral vein.
A hollow tube that is inserted into an artery.
Surgical creation of an external opening into the duodenum.
A hollow tube that is directed into the trachea from the mouth.
A hollow tube that is directed into the trachea from the nose.
A supraglottic airway device.
A hollow tube that is directed into the jejunum from the nose.
A hollow tube that is inserted into the pericardium through a surgical incision in the chest wall.
A hollow tube that is inserted into the pleural space through a surgical incision in the chest wall.

A tumor-associated core-region carbohydrate antigen of epithelial mucin, expressed in most colon carcinoma, mucinous carcinoma, pancreatic cancer, gastric, lung, breast, and ovarian carcinoma. Sialosyl-Tn (STn) antigen has been shown to be highly sensitive and a specific marker of colorectal cancer, associated with more aggressive diseases and poor prognosis. STn antigen and its immediate precursor, Tn antigen, are mucin type glycoprotein structures associated with the earliest steps of mucin O-linked glycosylation. When combined with a carrier molecule, keyhole limpet hemocyanin (KLH), this antigen may be co-administered with oral cyclophosphamide as an immune modulator.
The lower part of the stomach that connects to the duodenum.
A hollow tube that is directed into the colon from the rectum.
A finding indicating the involvement of sites other than the bone marrow by a hematopoietic neoplasm.
A finding indicating the involvement of the bone marrow and other anatomic sites, which may include the peripheral blood, lymph nodes, and/or extranodal sites, by a hematopoietic neoplasm.
An acute lymphoblastic or acute myeloid leukemia that occurs in infancy.
